### PHP OOP - Interfaces

Interfaces define a contract that implementing classes must follow.

### Defining an Interface

```php
<?php
interface Logger {
    public function log(string $message): void;
    public function getLogs(): array;
}
?>
```

### Implementing an Interface

```php
<?php
class FileLogger implements Logger {
    private array $logs = [];

    public function log(string $message): void {
        $this->logs[] = "[" . date("Y-m-d H:i:s") . "] $message";
    }

    public function getLogs(): array {
        return $this->logs;
    }
}

$logger = new FileLogger();
$logger->log("User logged in");
print_r($logger->getLogs());
?>
```

### Multiple Interfaces

PHP supports implementing multiple interfaces.

```php
<?php
interface JsonSerializable {
    public function toJson(): string;
}

interface Arrayable {
    public function toArray(): array;
}

class User implements JsonSerializable, Arrayable {
    public function toJson(): string {
        return json_encode($this->toArray());
    }

    public function toArray(): array {
        return ["name" => "John", "age" => 30];
    }
}
?>
```

### Interface Rules

| Rule | Description |
|------|-------------|
| Methods | Cannot have implementation |
| Properties | Cannot have properties |
| Visibility | Methods must be public |
| Constants | Can have constants |
| Multiple | A class can implement many interfaces |

### Type Hinting with Interfaces

```php
<?php
function processLogger(Logger $logger) {
    $logger->log("Processing...");
}

// Any class implementing Logger can be passed
processLogger(new FileLogger());
?>
```

> **Key Point:** Interfaces allow you to write code that works with any class that implements a given interface, enabling polymorphism and loose coupling.
